segments.text: This is an interview with General K. Hazell, H-A-L-S-E-L-L. Today's date is the 17th of September, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is a test.
Let's start off.
This is an interview with greater General
Okay, also, and today is the 17th of September 1981.
Let's talk about your parents first.
Let's start with your family background.
Can you tell us about that?
Well, my father and mother, who both died at the age of 82, my father was originally born in Bowling Green, Kentucky, and came to
protecting Waco in a covered wagon.
Do you remember approximately when that was?
Before the turn of the century.
It was, I'm sure, a very young man.
Very young.
My mother was born in Jefferson, Texas, and we courted and met her in Waco.
I have a sister who is deceased.
That was the extent of my immediate family.
What did your father do for occupation?
For many, many years, he was in the printing business.
As a young man, he started out as a plucky with Hill Printing Company in Waco.
In fact, I had and I cannot find them.
an annual that he printed of Texas A&M and TCU when it was at Waco in 1903.
Then he continued in the printing business.
I was born in Dallas, Texas.
October the 17th, 1913, 30 days from now.

Within six months of my birth, we moved to Kansas City, Missouri, where he was branch manager of a very old and very fine firm that's still in business with home office in Chicago called Barnhart Brothers in Spindler.
Is that printing also?
As a matter of fact, printing and presses, type, those things.
And then we returned to Dallas, where he was branch manager of a firm that's no longer in business, known as Millersaw Trimmer Company.
They make feeders, envelope cutters.
They sold type.
That's things like that.
As a matter of fact, the leading printing firm in Bryan at that time was known as Wallace Printing Company.
There is still a Wallace Printing Company, but it's the widow of one of the sons.
And my father was a very good friend of Marvin Wallace, the owner, because he used to call on us to travel.
In 1922, he was at a convention in Cleveland when he got a wire from his brother, Kate, also, asking him if he'd have a chance to buy a Dodge automobile business in Bryan, Texas.
Are you interested?
And he said, I wired back two words, hell yes.
And that's how we came to Bryan.

and then and then uh he was a half partner with with your with his brother his brother in the automotive that's right i was named after my uncle yeah it's very confusing because i've gone as and been known as chaos second all my life yet when i needed to
tell me about your mother she was raised in waco her she was
Her mother was with her when she was one year old.
She was raised there, and that's when she met Dad.
And she was a housewife all of her life.
Let's make sure that we're... What kind of man was your father?
Can you sort of describe him?
He was about
Five feet, seven inches tall, extremely wonderful personality.
He was a tremendous salesman.
If you'd like a story that he's told me that I thought was very good,
went to a new town called Clovis, New Mexico.
And the man had set up a printing firm.
And he went in to see him and just solicited his printing business.
And he said, I've already made up my mind what I'm going to buy and who I'm going to buy it from.
And Dad said, thank God this is a free country.
But he said, since you have already made up your mind, would you object if I looked at the list?
And he said, no, not at all.
And he said, well, I see that you're going to set up three alleys, by which he meant three printing alleys where the man said, yes.
He said, how did you know that?
He said, well, you've ordered to.

type number six point number eight point about like three a's or three b's three c's which indicate to me she wanted three alleys where three printers could work all at the same time without interfering with each other he said yes that's right and dad said well you may not be aware but i can sell you type by the lug guarantee the letter count and save you a ton of money and he said i had no idea
So he's a tremendous salesman.
What else about him?
Was he active in the community?
Yes.
In his earlier years, of course, he had a bad automobile accident in 1931.
broke his jaw, and they were unable to find in those days, by limited x-rays, exactly where it was broken.
And it appeared that he was not getting well, even to the extent of giving me a lift at the ball barracks.
And finally, the dentist and the doctor combined x-rays and x-rays and found the break.
And he sold out his interest in the business in the 30s to his brother.
Why did he do that?
Oh, it was, I think, difficult for two people to make a good living out of the same business.
And he had some rent property at the time.
It was up in the years, so he was getting retired.
How about your mother?
What kind of person was she?
She was a very loving person, and a very insecure person.
To understand that, you need to have known my grandmother.
possibly the 132nd or 164th Indian back then.
But my mother's father died when she was one year old.
And my grandma made my mother believe that if my grandmother didn't work, my mother would starve to death.
And I think she kind of had a syndrome like they received bills.
No matter how much money she had in the bank, she always wanted to where the next bill was coming from.
But she was a fine, fine person, a very loving person.
Who was the authority in the household?
My father.
So that's pretty much a traditional type family.
Yes.
Was religion at all important?
More so with my mother than my father.
We went, at least I went to Sunday school regularly.
Mother and dad went infrequently.
I went through all the usual things.
I belonged to the Episcopal Church and was an altar boy and all of those things.
It was...
a factor, perhaps not a real strong factor, but nevertheless it was there.
More so on my mother's side.
Now you eventually became a general, which is a position of leadership.
In what way do you think that your parents were responsible for that?
That's
Real difficult to say.
I know my father was afraid of no man.
Even when his jaw was broken, somebody said something one day to him, and he said, there's a chip on my shoulder.
Would you like to try to knock it off?
He was not afraid to say anything that he felt like.
I'll give you an example.
My former partner, Obie Donahue, was a salesman for Dad earlier.
And he said that year that Dodge trucks were the sorries that you ever laid your eyes on.
And he said a factory truck man came down and he said we called on everybody that was even thinking about buying a truck.
And the answer was no.
And he said, on the way back, I told the man that he's just going to have to start building a better truck if he wants to sell something.
So when they got back, the man went in to Dad and said, I want you to fire that salesman.
And Dad said, where's your money?
He said, what do you mean, where's my money?
Well, he said, if you're going to tell me how to run my business, it looks like you ought to have an investment in it.
He says, you sound like you'd like some contract cases.
He said, it's in the safe.
Do you want me to get it out?
He said, the man there ran it.
He was good with people, but he was wrong.
But in the early years...
I never saw my father except when he came in on the train on Friday night or Saturday morning and left Sunday night because he traveled by train.
So my discipline was an ivory back hairbrush from my mother.
And then I did bad the time Dad got home.
How much education did your parents have?
Not very much.
My father always remarked that he would love to have gone farther, but in the seventh grade he said he was minding his own business.

boy behind him threw a spitball and the teacher came up for the ruler and whacked him across the shoulder and he said i closed my book and hit her in the face and he said my last day of school was a superintendent and i was the principal in the classroom and i was running around throwing chalk at him as i went around got the door and went out and
He always regretted that he never had more education.
But in those days, seventh grade education was fairly good.
Let me check the call.
OK, let's talk about your education.
All right.
I entered Texas A&M.
Let's start before Texas A&M.
Let's start with your early education.
I went to kindergarten in Dallas, Texas.
We lived in the Oak Cliff section, which is now all colored.
I attended the first grade and second grade of Winnetka Elementary School, and I had started in the third grade, and we moved to Bryan about
seven or eight days before my ninth birthday.
And I entered the Bryan school system in third grade.
And I went through elementary school and high school all in the same building, which is now known as Fenton School.
In those days, we had
through the seventh grade was elementary school, and high school was eighth, ninth, 10th, and 11th.
And I graduated in 1931.
What were your favorite subjects?
English, history.
I had some particularly excellent teachers.
I can still almost to this day diagram a sentence which was purely from high school, not from university education.
We had some excellent teachers.
Were you in any sports or activities?
Football and basketball.
And then I went out for track by virtue of the fact that that was a way to escape physical education classes.
Why did you want to escape those?
Usually young men like those classes.
Well, I just thought I'd give track for it.
I think I had the record of running the mile in the longest time of anybody in the state.
I just went out to keep.
I played football and basketball.
I wasn't very good at either sport.
Did you consider yourself popular in high school?
Did you have a lot of friends?
Yes.
There was not a whole lot of people in my high school.
We had then, which is Boyd Elementary School.
I'm not sure what it was called then, but that was the west side.
And where we went to Bryan High School, which is currently Bannon, was the east side.
And we used to have football games on the courthouse lawn.
So many of my classmates are dead now.
Retired Judge Johnny M. Barron was a classmate.
He came over from the west side because his family was dead.
One of them in California named Charles Ferguson.
Charles and a man by the name of Sheik Wilcox and I were all the time running around together.
We didn't have as many clubs.
was in the debating team.
We didn't really have a lot of clubs.
It was fairly primitive back in those days.
I lived on what is now Texas Avenue.
It was in College Avenue, across from about where Midway Transmission is.
In fact, I think that Sonic Drive-in is where my home was.
And, of course, I walked home to lunch and walked back to school because it was only a matter of four or five blocks.
But nearly all of my classmates did.
Did you have any firm aims when you graduated from high school, or did you have any idea what you wanted to be or do in the future?
It was in the real height of the Depression.
Of course, the crash came in 29, the after effect.
In fact, my dad had to take on Kelvinator refrigerators just to keep the doors open.
I had no idea what I wanted to do, if there were any testing facilities.
They weren't known to me.
So dad suggested that I take engineering.
I said, well, that's all right.
He said, why not electrical engineering?
I said, OK, that's all right, which is not what I wanted to do at all.
And I took electrical engineering for 2 and 1 half years.
We got into polyphase lap wound motors, and I transferred to mechanical engineering.
Remember, again, it was hard, hard times.
Electrical engineers and mechanical engineers were graduating and getting jobs in filling stations.
My last year, I switched to agricultural engineering, who were getting more jobs than anybody else, and spent an extra year.
And I graduated in 1936 with a degree in agricultural engineering.
Did you ever consider any other university or college besides A&M?
I just would like to, but I was not able to afford it.
I'm not near one of my parents.
Although, believe it or not, for four years I lived in a dormitory there, even though my home was divided.
Why was that?
In those days, the lowest form of campus existence, and we had branches in the military, the lowest form of existence was a day student in the signal corps.
You didn't want to be a day student.
So I lived in Denver for four years.
I lived at home.
Why Stanford?
Why were you interested in Stanford?
It was an excellent university, and if I was going to study engineering, I felt like they had one of the top engineering schools in the United States.
Back in those days Were you eager to get out of Bryan College Station?
Were you eager to leave Texas to see something else?
Maybe, maybe to a degree.
I don't know.
I justmaybe it was
figment of imagination to dream something.
That's the only other place I ever even thought of.
Did the Depression, the Depression sounds like it had an economic impact on your family.
Did it have a political impact?
I mean, was your family a Roosevelt supporter or?
I, probably they were.
I'm not sure I was too interested in politics.
In those days,
You didn't get to vote until you were 21.
I remember we also paid a poll tax in Texas.
Except on my 21st birthday, I went down to the courthouse and got my certificate of eligibility to vote, and that was free.
I'm not sure I, as a lot of students, were doing it in politics.
I was pretty well wrapped up.
going to school.
Did your family ever accept any federal support during the Great Depression, or did anybody ever apply on a job?
To my knowledge, there was no federal support.
Oh, the CCCs, I'm talking about.
No.
A very close friend of mine was in the CCCs, a current close friend.
But no, I went to A&M.
Then they, I can't remember what year, possibly 32 or 33, they came out with what we call the AAA, the Agricultural Adjustment Act.
And one summer I worked from, went to school from 10 in the morning to 4 in the afternoon, worked from 4 in the afternoon to 12 at night.
The summer before, I surveyed acreage in the bottom.
Most of those people I already knew.
I walked many a mile around the fields.
But that job was funded by the government?
That's right.
It paid me $3 a day.
I worked seven days a week.
Finally worked up a supervisor, $4 a day, and they stopped the program.
What political persuasion was your family?
Democratic.
Yeah, everybody's Democratic in Texas.
At that time, were they conservatives, moderates, liberals?
Terry, I'm not sure.
Probably conservative.
Our political system in Bryan, we had a man, and he was a friend of Dad's, and he later became a rather good friend of mine.
He was an attorney named Law Henderson.
And I think Henderson Elementary School was named after him.
He was attorney for the city of Bryan, and he was attorney for Bryan Building and Home.
And he was the, I would say, the political czar of Brazos County.
Nobody ran for office and got elected without his approval.
And yet he was a fine person.
And I used to kid him because he smoked cigars for many years, and he quit.
He kept one stuck in his mouth.
And I used to kid him.
I said, Mr. Law, you're the only man I know with an unlighted chew of the back of your mouth.
But I liked him very much.
But he was a powerful politician.
And what political persuasion are you following?
I'm a conservative, very conservative Democrat.
Very conservative.
Now, when you went to A&M, did you ever consider the military aspect of A&M?
Was that at all important?
Or was it basically because of the engineering?
Yes, I think so.
I think so.
Of course, in those days,
The only people that were not in the Corps were either athletes or physically unqualified.
So it was just a matter of course going to the Corps.
Of course, you remember- Did that draw you, or did you have any feelings about being in the Corps or not being in the Corps?
I just assumed that was part of it.
As a matter of fact, I was in the registration line, and the seniors from the various outfits were there.
And one of them said, what outfit are you going to get in?
I said, I don't know.
He said, well, get in the Calvary.
I said, all right.
So farther down the line, there was another senior, and he said,
What outfit you gonna get in?
I said, the Calvary, I guess.
He said, what course you gonna take?
I said, electrical engineering.
He said, man, the Calvary hadn't graduated electrical engineering in 30 years.
I said, what do you represent?
He said, Battery A, field artillery.
I said, all right, I'll get the Battery A.
The next senior that came along was Battery C, field artillery, and he happened to be the last one I ran into, so I was in Battery C, field artillery.
Did you ever consider applying to one of the service academies?
I thought about it, but not probably real rigorously.
But I took to the military.
What did you like about being on the Corps?
Cam ready, friendship.
I had a ball as a freshman.
In those days, we'd cut our hair short.
We had a white stripe around our cup.
Do they still have that?
No.
A freshman had many privileges you might not be aware of.
For example?
We could cut in on a senior to dance.
say, pardon me, sir, but I'd like to thank this lady.
Or we could walk up to any guest young lady on campus and introduce her.
I'm Fish Austin.
She better meet you.
That a ball, really.
Of course, those days we had boards.
Yeah.
Tell me about the hazing.
Well, I went out for freshman football.
Mind you, I would...
What, 145, 150 pounds.
And I was a center and linebacker in high school.
I ended up as a third string quarterback, which is meat grinding.
And we had what was known then as a frog.
You ever hear of a frog?
A frog was an individual that started mid-term.
So he had to play freshman football the following year.
He wasn't a fish, he was a frog.
And they'd open up a line, and I'd dash through it, and there's a big old boy, and he'd pick me up, flap me like that, and the ball would go that way, and the helmet that way.
How long did you last play football?
I played through the whole year.
On the third string, of course, that was way down the line.
That was, well, I'd say it was a cannon fodder.
But I enjoyed it.
Did you play any after that?
No, only intramural.
I played intramural.
And intramural softball.
And your work?
Work was primarily in the summertime.
But not during the school year?
No.
And yet you still had enough money to be able to live on campus and not work during the school year during the Depression?
That's right.
That was my mother and father's time.
But money went a long way, you see.
Oh, yeah.
Money went a long way.
And I guess the room and board at the university college at that time was about as cheap as living at home.
Did you see any purpose in the hazing?
Yes.
What was it?
Of course, it varied among outfits.
In our battery,
Only the sophomores hazed the freshmen.
The juniors and seniors could.
And in some instances, they did.
But we had some unwritten rules.
A sophomore or a junior could only call for a specific freshman to run an errand.
A senior could holler freshman, and all of them would scurry.
That first year in A&M, we had room inspections every Saturday morning.
And I cleaned up for the battery commander and his roommate, and for the first sergeant and his roommate.
Remember, we had very few freshmen.
I think the total enrollment
In 1931, total enrollment was around 0.5.
And the battery commander was left-handed.
And you had to assume a certain position with the testicle, handle of the testicle.
And then the battery commander would
strike me three or four times with the board, and then his roommate, who was right-handed, and they didn't want to know which hit the hardest.
And then I had to be very delicate about how the techniques were different and so forth, because obviously the one that you said hit the hardest doesn't have to prove anything wrong.
And the first sergeant, who was commonly a junior in his roommates,
I would work Friday afternoon mopping the floor and cleaning it up.
Come in Saturday morning to make the last touch and they'd been eating pecans and they were all over the floor.
And then I found out that they didn't inspect the first sergeant's room.
So it made it a whole lot easier.
But it was, hazing was kind of a way of life.
It wasn't done in brutality really.

it was done to see a lot of people come out of high school big man on campus and all of that one of the things that we did i don't know whether i was smart enough but i was lucky enough every unit that started school each company about first sergeant would make an announcement
Due to the shortage of non-commissioned officers, there were vacancies, and anybody that would like to apply for those vacancies, please step forward.
So some freshmen stepped forward, and they were appointed everything from master sergeant to corporal.
But they were on a probationary period, and they had to wear their stripes upside down.
Well, they made the announcements on the PA system
Sabisa Hall, big man on campus till the day of wreck.
It was all a part of the tradition of bringing you into discipline.
So you thought that Hastings was part of the purpose of this tradition and discipline?
I think so.
Are you sorry to see it go?
It's about the only thing they have today on campus.
No, not really.
This is a different time, different time frame.
I'm hard pressed to advise my son in many instances because the times are different.
Communication is instant like that.
things that occurred 30 minutes ago we were aware of.
Not in those days.
It's just a whole different ballgame.
I think hazing had its place at that time.
I do not think it does now.
Was there anything that you disliked about being on the Corps?
I can't think of a thing.
I marched the mill three times a day.
Many a time we had to steal
food to bring it to a senior.
Even though we had a regular army mat to start and stand at the door, it was quite a challenge.
I loved it, really.
Had a ball.
Did you ever assume a position of leadership in the Corps?
I was slated to be first sergeant of Battery City.
And I failed to qualify as a junior.
Poor grades.
And the sergeant major down in the commandant's office, I'd go down there, and he says, there's Kay Hawson, the guy with his military future behind you.
So I became a file closer to my junior year and my senior.
And in my fifth year, I became a second lieutenant.
When I came back, it was qualified.
Let's talk about the ways in which being in the Corps helped you in your military career.
Things we did were practical.
To give you an example, if I may move forward a while.
In 1941, I was a volunteer in practice duty and went to Fort Ord, California and was sent to a school of 7th Division artillery.
Then we went to
Camp Roberts, California, which was an IRTC, Infra-Replacement Training Center, in the West Garrison.
In the East Garrison, which was designed for an artillery brigade, we went there to form the 26th Field Artillery Brigade.
We had
In our regiment, 70 officers, of which 40 were regular army, and 30 were reserve.
Many of them of which were up and down the California coast, San Jose State, Stanford, and various places around.
They were unable to move a body of men.
They were unable to properly salute.
They really were.
That was old stuff to me.
In other words, the way it helped you was preparation.
That's right.
Because, see, we were horse-drawn artillery.
And I liked horses.
And we had some fine stable sergeants and army sergeants, regular army down there.
And freshmen either rode the caisson.
You know what a caisson is?
a two-wheel vehicle that pulls the gun.
Or he rides the first team.
And then generally, sophomores ride the swing team or the lead team.
There'll be three horses.
And you rode on the left side or the near horse, and you had a horse on the other side, the off horse.
As a sophomore, I was a lead team driver.
And I had an off horse by the name of Santa Claus, I believe.
The only time he ever, the only way he ever went out of the gun park was on his hind legs.
So I had a barrel.
Is there any way you think that being in the Corps ever hurt your advancement, hindered in any way your career in the military?
No.
I'd say it absolutely enhanced it.
Has it prepared you much better than the average ROTC person?
Yes.
On the West Coast, they wore the uniform on drill day.
And we lived it.
We marched to meals three times a day in formation.
We had parades and reviews.
It was just a way of life.
But we differed in one way with our military staff.
A few of them that were
over-anxious, I guess the wording is.
We'd call our dormitories barracks.
And every so often as they, those over-ambitious would pass by, they accidentally got wet out of the window.
And they didn't know who did it.
We harassed them.
But we had a, you know, a closeness of spirit.
We had a
Well, it was the Democrats and Republicans.
Artillery wore red hat cards on their hats.
Infantry wore blue.
We used to have elections they called hat card elections.
But the Corps was really a close-knit out.
Do you think that being in the Corps had any impact on you eventually becoming a general?
I can't see how it would help.
You did not become an officer until you were a senior.
You did not become a sergeant until you were a classified junior.
I became, I think, a corporal when I was a sophomore.
Some institutions you can become a sergeant and a sophomore and so forth.
We had what we called tactical officers.
Let's talk about some of these.
These are professional soldiers.
What impact did they have on you?
Quite a bit.
When I was a freshman, I had a very fine and gentle soul by the name of Captain Tom Harris.
And of course, remember that the
Army had no money in those days.
Captain Harry told me one day, he said, well, I see where old General so-and-so died.
I went up one notch on the promotion list.
And in what we call military science class, or we call bulletics, we were talking about the then gun, the French 75.
